olestan Palace: A Window into the Soci al Hi story of Iran during the Qajar Era -- tHow a Former Museum of Modern Art Curator Assembled an International History of Photography Collection for Iran in the 1970s -- tWorks Cited -- tLIST OF CONTRIBUTORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe historiography of early photography has scarcely examined Islamic countries in the Near and Middle East, although the new technique was adopted very quickly there by the 1840s. Which regional, local, and global aspects can be made evident? What role did autochthonous image and art traditions have, and which specific functions did photography meet since its introduction? This collective volume deals with examples from Iran, the Ottoman Empire, and the Arab lands and with the question of local specifics, or an „indigenous lens." The contributions broach the issues of regional histories of photography, local photographers, specific themes and practices, and historical collections in these countries. They offer, for the first time in book form, a cross-section through a developing field of the history of photography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPhotographyzMiddle EastxHistoryy19th century. 7aPhotography / Subjects & Themes / Regional (see also TRAVEL / Pictorials).2bisacsh1 aAkcan, Esra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaleva, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEldem, Edhem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Carmen Pérez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelbig, Elahe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNabipour, Alireza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu